               <head>The first part. Of the Law and Obedience.</head>
               <sp who="a">
                  <p>Ma. <notvariant>Forasmuch</notvariant> as our Obedience, whereof we<lb/>
<normalised orig="haue" auto="true">have</normalised> first to <normalised orig="speake" auto="true">speak</normalised>, it to be <normalised orig="tryed" auto="true">tried</normalised> by the rule of the<lb/>
law of God, it is necessary that we first search out the<lb/>
whole substance &amp; nature of the Law: which being<lb/>
found and <normalised orig="knowen" auto="true">known</normalised>, it can not be <normalised orig="vnknowen" auto="true">unknown</normalised>, what<lb/>
and of what sort our obedience ought to be. Therefore<lb/>
<normalised orig="beginne" auto="true">begin</normalised> to tell what thou <normalised orig="thinkest" auto="true">think</normalised> of the Law.<lb/>
                  </p>
               </sp>
               <sp who="b">
                  <p><notvariant>Sch</notvariant>. I <normalised orig="thinke" auto="true">think</normalised> that the law of God is the full,<lb/>
and in all <normalised orig="pointes" auto="true">points</normalised> perfect, rule of the <normalised orig="righteousnesse" auto="true">righteousness</normalised><lb/>
that is required of man, which <normalised orig="commaundeth" auto="true">commands</normalised><lb/>
those things that are to be done, and <normalised orig="forbiddeth" auto="true">forbids</normalised><lb/>
the contraries. In this law God <normalised orig="hath" auto="true">has</normalised> restrained<lb/>
all <normalised orig="thinges" auto="true">things</normalised> to his <normalised orig="owne" auto="true">own</normalised> will and <normalised orig="iudgement" auto="true">judgment</normalised>,<lb/>
so as no <normalised orig="godlinesse" auto="true">godliness</normalised> toward him, nor <normalised orig="dutifulnesse" auto="true">dutifulness</normalised><lb/>
toward men, can be allowed of him, but<lb/>
that <normalised orig="onely" auto="true">only</normalised> which <normalised orig="doth" auto="false">does</normalised> in all <normalised orig="thinges" auto="true">things</normalised> agree with<lb/>
the <normalised orig="streightnesse" auto="true">straightness</normalised> of this rule. <normalised orig="Uainely" auto="false">Vainly</normalised> therefore<lb/>
do <normalised orig="mortall" auto="true">mortal</normalised> men <normalised orig="inuent" auto="true">invent</normalised> to <normalised orig="themselues" auto="true">themselves</normalised> <normalised orig="formes" auto="true">forms</normalised> of<lb/>
<normalised orig="godlinesse" auto="true">godliness</normalised> and <normalised orig="dutie" auto="true">duty</normalised> after their <normalised orig="owne" auto="true">own</normalised> <normalised orig="fansie" auto="true">fancy</normalised>.<lb/>
For God <normalised orig="hath" auto="true">has</normalised> set forth to <normalised orig="vs" auto="true">us</normalised> his law written in<lb/>
two Tables as most sure rule both of our worshipping<lb/>
of God and of our duties to men,<lb/>
and therewith also <normalised orig="hath" auto="true">has</normalised> declared that there is<lb/>
nothing on earth more pleasant and acceptable<lb/>
to him than our obedience.<lb/>
                  </p>
               </sp>
               <sp who="a">
                  <p>Ma. Whereof <normalised orig="treateth" auto="true">treats</normalised> the first Table?<lb/>
                  </p>
               </sp>
               <sp who="b">
                  <p><notvariant>Sch</notvariant>. It <normalised orig="treateth" auto="true">treats</normalised> of our <normalised orig="Godlinesse" auto="true">Godliness</normalised> toward<lb/>
God, and <normalised orig="conteineth" auto="true">contains</normalised> the first <normalised orig="fower" auto="true">four</normalised> <normalised orig="commaundementes" auto="true">commandments</normalised><lb/>
of the law.<lb/>
                  </p>
               </sp>
               <sp who="a">
                  <p>Ma. Whereof <normalised orig="treateth" auto="true">treats</normalised> the second?<lb/>
                  </p>
               </sp>
               <fw type="pageNum">C.<notvariant>ij</notvariant>.</fw>
               <pb n="1"/>
               <sp who="b">
                  <p><notvariant>Sch</notvariant>. Of the duties of <normalised orig="mutuall" auto="true">mutual</normalised> <normalised orig="Charitie" auto="true">Charity</normalised> or <normalised orig="loue" auto="true">love</normalised><lb/>
among men, which <normalised orig="conteineth" auto="true">contains</normalised> <normalised orig="sixe" auto="true">six</normalised> <normalised orig="commandementes" auto="false">commandments</normalised>.<lb/>
And so in a <normalised orig="summe" auto="false">sum</normalised>, ten <normalised orig="commandementes" auto="false">commandments</normalised><lb/>
make <normalised orig="vp" auto="true">up</normalised> the whole law. For which cause<lb/>
the law is called the Ten <normalised orig="commandementes" auto="false">commandments</normalised>.<lb/>
                  </p>
               </sp>
               <sp who="a">
                  <p>Ma. Rehearse me the first <normalised orig="commandement" auto="true">commandment</normalised> of the<lb/>
first table.<lb/>
                  </p>
               </sp>
               <sp who="b">
                  <p><notvariant>Sch</notvariant>. God <normalised orig="spake" auto="true">spoke</normalised> thus. <quote type="biblical" ana="Ex 20.2-3"><normalised orig="Heare" auto="true">Hear</normalised> O <normalised orig="Israell" auto="false">Israel</normalised>: I am the Lord<lb/>
thy God which <normalised orig="haue" auto="true">have</normalised> brought thee out of the land of <normalised orig="Egipt" auto="true">Egypt</normalised>,<lb/>
out of the house of bondage. Thou shalt <normalised orig="haue" auto="true">have</normalised> none other<lb/>
Gods before me.</quote>
                     <lb/>
                     <lb/>
                  </p>
               </sp>
               <sp who="a">
                  <p>Ma. Why <normalised orig="doth" auto="false">does</normalised> God first <normalised orig="speake" auto="true">speak</normalised> somewhat of <normalised orig="himselfe" auto="true">himself</normalised><lb/>
and of his <normalised orig="benefite" auto="true">benefit</normalised>?<lb/>
                  </p>
               </sp>
               <sp who="b">
                  <p><notvariant>Sch</notvariant>. He had principally care that the estimation<lb/>
of the <normalised orig="lawes" auto="true">laws</normalised> <normalised orig="ordeined" auto="true">ordained</normalised> by him, should not be<lb/>
shortly abated by contempt. And therefore that<lb/>
they might <normalised orig="haue" auto="true">have</normalised> the greater <normalised orig="authoritie" auto="true">authority</normalised>, he <normalised orig="vseth" auto="false">uses</normalised><lb/>
this as it were an <normalised orig="entrie" auto="true">entry</normalised>, <quote type="biblical" ana="Ex 20.2">I am the Lord thy God.</quote>
                     <lb/>
In which <normalised orig="wordes" auto="true">words</normalised> he <normalised orig="teacheth" auto="true">teaches</normalised> that he is our<lb/>
maker, lord and <normalised orig="sauiour" auto="true">saviour</normalised>, and the author of all<lb/>
good. And so with good right by his <normalised orig="dignitie" auto="true">dignity</normalised> of a<lb/>
Lawmaker, he <normalised orig="chalengeth" auto="true">challenges</normalised> to <normalised orig="himselfe" auto="true">himself</normalised> the <normalised orig="authoritie" auto="true">authority</normalised><lb/>
of commanding: and by his <normalised orig="goodnesse" auto="true">goodness</normalised>, he<lb/>
<normalised orig="procureth" auto="true">procures</normalised> <normalised orig="fauour" auto="true">favour</normalised> to his law: and by them both together,<lb/>
<normalised orig="burdeneth" auto="true">burdens</normalised> <normalised orig="vs" auto="true">us</normalised> with <normalised orig="necessitie" auto="true">necessity</normalised> to obey it,<lb/>
                     <choice ana="illegible">
                        <sic>v*<normalised orig="lesse" auto="true">less</normalised></sic>
                        <corr><normalised orig="vnlesse" auto="true">unless</normalised></corr>
                     </choice> we will be both <normalised orig="rebelles" auto="true">rebels</normalised> against him<lb/>
that is most mighty, and <normalised orig="vnthankefull" auto="true">unthankful</normalised> toward<lb/>
him that is most <normalised orig="bountifull" auto="true">bountiful</normalised>.<lb/>
                  </p>
               </sp>
               <sp who="a">
                  <p>Ma. But <normalised orig="wheras" auto="true">whereas</normalised> he <normalised orig="speaketh" auto="true">speaks</normalised> of Israel by name,<lb/>
and <normalised orig="maketh" auto="true">makes</normalised> expressly mention of breaking the yoke<lb/>
of the bondage of Egypt: <normalised orig="doth" auto="false">does</normalised> not this belong <normalised orig="onely" auto="true">only</normalised><lb/>
to the people of Israel?<lb/>
                  </p>
               </sp>
               <sp who="b">
                  <p><notvariant>Sch</notvariant>. God in <normalised orig="deede" auto="true">deed</normalised> rescued the Israelites by his<lb/>
<normalised orig="seruant" auto="true">servant</normalised> Moses from bodily bondage, but he<lb/>
                     <pb n="2"/>
                     <lb/>
<normalised orig="hath" auto="true">has</normalised> <normalised orig="deliuered" auto="true">delivered</normalised> all them that be his, by his <normalised orig="sonne" auto="true">son</normalised><lb/>
<normalised orig="Iesus" auto="true">Jesus</normalised> Christ from the <normalised orig="spirituall" auto="true">spiritual</normalised> <normalised orig="thraldome" auto="true">thraldom</normalised> of<lb/>
<normalised orig="sinne" auto="true">sin</normalised>, and the <normalised orig="tyrannie" auto="true">tyranny</normalised> of the <normalised orig="Deuill" auto="true">Devil</normalised>, <normalised orig="wherin" auto="true">wherein</normalised> <normalised orig="els" auto="true">else</normalised><lb/>
they had lien pressed and oppressed. This <normalised orig="kinde" auto="true">kind</normalised><lb/>
of <normalised orig="deliuerance" auto="true">deliverance</normalised> <normalised orig="perteineth" auto="true">pertained</normalised> indifferently to all<lb/>
men, which put their trust in God their <normalised orig="deliuerer" auto="true">deliverer</normalised>,<lb/>
&amp; do to their power obey his <normalised orig="lawes" auto="true">laws</normalised>. Which<lb/>
if they do not, he <normalised orig="doth" auto="false">does</normalised> by this <normalised orig="rehearsall" auto="true">rehearsal</normalised> of his<lb/>
most great benefit pronounce that they <normalised orig="shalbe" auto="true">shall be</normalised><lb/>
<normalised orig="gilty" auto="false">guilty</normalised> of most great <normalised orig="vnthankfulnesse" auto="true">unthankfulness</normalised>. For let <normalised orig="euery" auto="true">every</normalised><lb/>
man imagine the <normalised orig="Deuill" auto="true">Devil</normalised> that hellish <normalised orig="Pharao" auto="true">Pharaoh</normalised><lb/>
ready to <normalised orig="oppresse" auto="true">oppress</normalised> him, and how <normalised orig="sinne" auto="true">sin</normalised> is that<lb/>
most <normalised orig="foule" auto="true">foul</normalised> mier wherein he most <notvariant>filthily</notvariant> <normalised orig="walloweth" auto="true">wallows</normalised>,<lb/>
let him set before the eyes of his <normalised orig="minde" auto="true">mind</normalised> hell<lb/>
the most wretched Egyptian bondage, and then<lb/>
shall he easily <normalised orig="perceaue" auto="true">perceive</normalised> that this <normalised orig="freedome" auto="true">freedom</normalised> <normalised orig="wherof" auto="true">whereof</normalised><lb/>
I <normalised orig="speake" auto="true">speak</normalised> is the thing that he ought principally<lb/>
to desire, as the thing of most great importance<lb/>
to him, whereof yet he shall be most <normalised orig="vnworthy" auto="true">unworthy</normalised>,<lb/>
<normalised orig="vnlesse" auto="true">unless</normalised> he <normalised orig="honor" auto="true">honour</normalised> the author of his <normalised orig="deliuerance" auto="true">deliverance</normalised><lb/>
<normalised orig="withall" auto="true">withal</normalised> <normalised orig="seruice" auto="true">service</normalised> and obedience.<lb/>
                  </p>
               </sp>
               <sp who="a">
                  <p>Ma. Say on.<lb/>
                  </p>
               </sp>
               <sp who="b">
                  <p><notvariant>Sch</notvariant>. After that he <normalised orig="hath" auto="true">has</normalised> thus <normalised orig="stablished" auto="false">established</normalised> the <normalised orig="authoritie" auto="true">authority</normalised><lb/>
of his law, now <normalised orig="foloweth" auto="true">follows</normalised> the <normalised orig="commandement" auto="true">commandment</normalised>.<lb/>
                     <quote type="biblical" ana="Ex 20.3">Thou shalt <normalised orig="haue" auto="true">have</normalised> none other Gods before me.</quote>
